In TypeScript, you can find mutual connections between different types using the "intersection" type. An intersection type combines multiple types into one, creating a type that has all the properties and methods of each of the original types. To create an intersection type, you use the "&" operator.

For example, let's say you have two types, "Person" and "Employee", and you want to create a new type "Manager" that is both a Person and an Employee. The Manager type would have all the properties and methods of both the Person and Employee types. You could do this like so:
```
type Person = {
    name: string;
    age: number;
};

type Employee = {
    employeeId: number;
    salary: number;
};

type Manager = Person & Employee;

const manager: Manager = {
    name: 'John Doe',
    age: 35,
    employeeId: 123,
    salary: 50000
};
```
In this example, the Manager type has all the properties of the Person and Employee types, and you can use it like you would use a Person or an Employee.

Another way to combine multiple types is using 'union' types. That is combining types using '|' operator. Union types represent a value that can be one of several types.
```
type A = { a: string };
type B = { b: string };
type C = A | B;

const c: C = { a: 'string' }  // this is valid
const c: C = { b: 'string' }  // this is also valid
```
Here variable `c` can be of type A or type B

You can also use type alias to achieve the same.
```
type Person = {
    name: string;
    age: number;
};

type Employee = {
    employeeId: number;
    salary: number;
};

type Manager = {
    ...Person,
    ...Employee
}
```
It creates a new type that has all the properties of Person and Employee.

Here's an example of a function in TypeScript that finds the path between two users with a degree of separation, given an array of users and their connections:
```
interface User {
    name: string;
    connections: string[];
}

interface Path {
    user: User;
    degree: number;
}

function findPath(users: User[], start: string, end: string): Path[] | null {
    // create an empty queue for the breadth-first search
    const queue: Path[] = [];
    // create a set to keep track of visited users
    const visited = new Set<string>();
    // add the starting user to the queue with a degree of separation of 0
    queue.push({ user: users.find(user => user.name === start)!, degree: 0 });
    // while the queue is not empty
    while (queue.length > 0) {
        // dequeue the next user
        const path = queue.shift()!;
        const user = path.user;
        // check if the user has been visited
        if (!visited.has(user.name)) {
            // mark the user as visited
            visited.add(user.name);
            // if the user is the end user, return the path
            if (user.name === end) {
                return [path];
            }
            // for each of the user's connections
            for (const connection of user.connections) {
                // get the connected user
                const connectedUser = users.find(user => user.name === connection);
                if (connectedUser) {
                    // add the connected user to the queue with a degree of separation of path.degree + 1
                    queue.push({ user: connectedUser, degree: path.degree + 1 });
                }
            }
        }
    }
    // if the end user is not found, return null
    return null;
}
```
This function uses breadth-first search (BFS) algorithm to find the path. The basic idea of the BFS algorithm is to explore all the neighboring nodes before exploring the next level of nodes.
It starts with the start user, adds it to a queue and mark it visited. Then it dequeues the next user, checks if the user is the end user, if not, it adds the user's connections to the queue and increment their degree of separation.
it does this untill it finds the end user or until the queue is empty.

You can use this function to find the path between two users in the format of `[{user: User, degree: number}]` where user is a user object and degree is the number of the degree of separation. If there is no path then it returns null.
