To create a CUDA program for vector addition using multithreading, the following steps need to be followed:

1. Initialize CUDA: First, you need to initialize the CUDA environment on your device by including the required headers and libraries.
2. Allocate memory on the GPU: Next, allocate memory on the GPU for the input vectors and the result vector. This can be done using the CUDA runtime API's "cudaMalloc" function.
3. Copy data to the GPU: After allocating memory, you need to copy the data of the input vectors from the host to the GPU memory using the "cudaMemcpy" function.
4. Define the kernel: Next, define a CUDA kernel that performs the vector addition operation. In this kernel, each thread will perform the addition of corresponding elements of the two input vectors.
5. Launch the kernel: After defining the kernel, launch the kernel using the "cudaLaunchKernel" function, passing the number of threads per block and the number of blocks as arguments.
6. Synchronize the threads: After launching the kernel, synchronize the threads to ensure that all the threads in the block have completed the vector addition operation. This can be done using the "cudaDeviceSynchronize" function.
7. Copy the result from GPU to CPU: Finally, copy the result from the GPU memory to the host memory using the "cudaMemcpy" function.
8. Clean up: After the computation is complete, free the memory allocated on the GPU using the "cudaFree" function and release any other resources.

The following is a sample code for the vector addition using CUDA:
```scss
#include <cuda.h>

__global__ void addVectors(float *A, float *B, float *C, int N) {
  int i = blockDim.x * blockIdx.x + threadIdx.x;
  if (i < N) C[i] = A[i] + B[i];
}

int main(void) {
  float *A, *B, *C;
  int N = 256;
  int size = N * sizeof(float);
  cudaMalloc((void **)&A, size);
  cudaMalloc((void **)&B, size);
  cudaMalloc((void **)&C, size);
  cudaMemcpy(A, h_A, size, cudaMemcpyHostToDevice);
  cudaMemcpy(B, h_B, size, cudaMemcpyHostToDevice);
  addVectors<<<1, 256>>>(A, B, C, N);
  cudaMemcpy(h_C, C, size, cudaMemcpyDeviceToHost);
  cudaFree(A);
  cudaFree(B);
  cudaFree(C);
  return 0;
}
```
In this code, `h_A` and `h_B` are the input vectors on the host and `h_C` is the result vector on the host. The kernel `addVectors` is launched with one block and 256 threads per block.

