```c
#include <iostream>
#include <omp.h>

using namespace std;

int main() {
    int credit_completed = 0;
    int credit_pending = 0;
    int total_credit = 120;
    int back_log = 0;

    #pragma omp parallel num_threads(6) default(none) shared(credit_completed, credit_pending, total_credit, back_log)
    {
        int tid = omp_get_thread_num();
        if (tid < 2) {
            #pragma omp atomic
            credit_completed += 30;
        }
        else {
            #pragma omp atomic
            credit_pending += total_credit - credit_completed - back_log;
        }
    }

    cout << "Credit Completed: " << credit_completed << endl;
    cout << "Credit Pending: " << credit_pending << endl;

    return 0;
}
```
In this code, we have created a maximum of 6 threads and scheduled the process using dynamic scheduling. The `num_threads(6)` clause specifies the maximum number of threads to be created. The `default(none)` clause specifies that no variables are shared by default. The `shared` clause specifies the shared variables `credit_completed`, `credit_pending`, `total_credit`, and `back_log`.

The code calculates the total number of credits completed by the student at the end of the third semester using two threads (thread ID less than 2) and calculates the number of credits yet to be registered to complete the course, considering any back log that exists, using the remaining threads (thread ID greater than 2). The `omp_get_thread_num()` function returns the thread ID, and the `#pragma omp atomic` directive ensures that the updates to `credit_completed` and `credit_pending` are atomic and thread-safe.

