To create a Kafka stream and send write records to Kafka topic, we need to add the following code:

Step 1: Create a KafkaProducerConfig class that defines the Kafka producer configuration. Here's an example code for the configuration:
```typescript
@Configuration
public class KafkaProducerConfig {
    @Value("${spring.kafka.bootstrap-servers}")
    private String bootstrapServers;

    @Bean
    public ProducerFactory<String, String> producerFactory() {
        Map<String, Object> configProps = new HashMap<>();
        configProps.put(ProducerConfig.BOOTSTRAP_SERVERS_CONFIG, bootstrapServers);
        configProps.put(ProducerConfig.KEY_SERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG, StringSerializer.class);
        configProps.put(ProducerConfig.VALUE_SERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG, StringSerializer.class);
        return new DefaultKafkaProducerFactory<>(configProps);
    }

    @Bean
    public KafkaTemplate<String, String> kafkaTemplate() {
        return new KafkaTemplate<>(producerFactory());
    }
}
```
Step 2: Add the KafkaProducerConfig to the main application class.

Step 3: Modify the REST endpoints to send the write records to the Kafka topic. Here's an example code for the createState() method:
```less
@Autowired
private KafkaTemplate<String, String> kafkaTemplate;

@PostMapping("")
public Mono<State> createState(@RequestBody State state) {
    state.setCreatedAt(Instant.now());
    state.setUpdatedAt(Instant.now());
    Mono<State> savedState = stateRepository.save(state);
    savedState.subscribe(saved -> {
        String record = "Created " + saved.getClass().getSimpleName() + " with ID " + saved.getId();
        kafkaTemplate.send("write-topic", record);
    });
    return savedState;
}
```
