Yes, you can add a delay to mouseover and mouseout events using `setTimeout` function. To override the last firing of the event, you can use a `clearTimeout` function, that would clear the previous `setTimeout` before setting a new one. This will ensure that only one event listener is active at a time.

Here's an example:
```scss
let timeoutId = null;

ratingButtons.forEach((button, index) => {
  button.addEventListener("mouseover", () => {
    if (timeoutId !== null) {
      clearTimeout(timeoutId);
    }
    timeoutId = setTimeout(() => {
      hoveredButton = index;
      updateButtonsClasses();
    }, 200);
  });

  button.addEventListener("mouseout", () => {
    if (timeoutId !== null) {
      clearTimeout(timeoutId);
    }
    timeoutId = setTimeout(() => {
      hoveredButton = -1;
      updateButtonsClasses();
    }, 200);
  });
});
```
In the above example, we have used a `timeoutId` variable to store the `setTimeout` ID, and a `clearTimeout` function to clear it before setting a new one. The `setTimeout` function takes two arguments: the function to execute and the delay time in milliseconds. In the example, we have set the delay to 200 milliseconds.

It is not considered bad practice to use setTimeout for adding a delay to event handlers, but it is not the only option. A common alternative is to use debouncing, which is a technique for controlling the frequency of function calls by limiting the rate at which the function can be executed. The idea is to only call the function once a certain amount of time has passed since the last call, effectively "bouncing" or delaying subsequent calls until the interval has passed.

One popular library for debouncing is Lodash, which has a debounce function that you can use in your code. However, you can also implement debouncing yourself with a simple function.

For example:
```javascript
let debounceTimeoutId;

function debouncedFunction() {
  // Function logic here
}

element.addEventListener("mouseover", function() {
  clearTimeout(debounceTimeoutId);
  debounceTimeoutId = setTimeout(debouncedFunction, 250);
});
```
In this example, the debouncedFunction will only be executed once 250 milliseconds have passed since the last mouseover event. This will prevent the function from firing too frequently and also ensure that only one function call is active at a time, effectively "cancelling" any previous calls if a new mouseover event occurs before the previous call has finished.

