To handle incoming calls in a 3rd-party application using the Microsoft Graph API, you will need to set up a webhook to receive notifications when a call is incoming.

A webhook is a way to receive real-time notifications from the Microsoft Graph API.

Here is an example of how to set up a webhook in JavaScript:
```
fetch("https://graph.microsoft.com/v1.0/subscriptions", {
  method: "POST",
  headers: {
    Authorization: "Bearer " + accessToken,
    "Content-Type": "application/json"
  },
  body: JSON.stringify({
    changeType: "created,updated",
    notificationUrl: "https://your-webhook-url.com/notifications",
    resource: "calls",
    expirationDateTime: "2022-01-01T00:00:00.0000000Z",
    clientState: "secretClientValue"
  })
}).then(response => {
    // Handle the response from the API
});
```
In this example, the webhook will send a notification to the specified "notificationUrl" endpoint each time a call is created or updated. The "changeType" parameter is used to specify the types of changes for which the webhook should send notifications. The "resource" parameter specifies that the webhook should be triggered for call resources. The "expirationDateTime" parameter specifies the date and time after which the webhook will expire. And the "clientState" parameter is an optional parameter that allows you to include a string value that will be included in the notification, so you can identify the origin of the webhook.

Once the webhook is set up, your application will receive a notification each time a call is incoming, and you can handle it accordingly.

It is important to note that you'll need the proper permissions to subscribe and manage the webhooks, you can check the documentation on how to grant permissions and configure your application.

