You can use the `.catch()` method of a returned promise in conjunction with Jest's `expect(fn).toThrow()` method to test that an async method throws a specific error.
Here is an example:
```
import axios from 'axios';

test('throws a 404 error', async () => {
  const fakeId = 'not-found';
  const axiosCall = axios.get(`/api/users/${fakeId}`);
  await expect(axiosCall).rejects.toThrow('Request failed with status code 404');
});
```
Another way:
```
test('throws a 404 error', async () => {
  const fakeId = 'not-found';
  try {
    await axios.get(`/api/users/${fakeId}`);
  } catch (error) {
    expect(error.response.status).toEqual(404);
  }
});
```
Keep in mind that the first approach will only work if your API is configured to return the http status code in the error message and the second approach is more specific to axios.
Also, you may want to provide proper error message instead of 'Request failed with status code 404'

